Dear Hiring Team, 

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the Software Engineer position with Essen Health Care. I bring over three years of professional experience in full-stack development, AI automations, and LLM-powered systems, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered production-grade systems that directly reflect the technical depth and end-to-end ownership this position demands. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I architected AI automations using LLMs that translate natural-language intents into safe, validated tool calls across 1,000+ endpoints—requiring rigorous API contract design, input validation, and edge case handling across distributed systems. I implemented a full observability layer using Langfuse and LangSmith, covering tracing, structured logging, and evaluation hooks, reducing end-to-end latency by 60% and LLM API costs by 50% through targeted concurrency and routing optimizations. I also developed data pipelines and concurrent multi-agent orchestration using LangChain and LangGraph, enabling scalable execution with system design patterns for reliability—experience that translates directly to building clinical rules engines and AI automations that interact with complex healthcare systems. Prior to Sperse, as a Software Engineer at Qualitest, I built an internal support chatbot using LangChain and RAG with a PostgreSQL vector store, reducing ticket resolution time by 20% through LLM-powered retrieval—demonstrating my ability to apply AI to improve operational workflows. I also contributed to a full-stack Identity & Access Management platform built with React, Spring Boot, and AWS, supporting thousands of users across 30+ applications, and developed backend workflows using AWS Step Functions to handle long-running data import jobs, writing tests and implementing deployment tooling for reliable production releases. Together, these roles have prepared me to take well-scoped technical work and ship it end to end, including features, integrations, bug fixes, and infrastructure improvements.

My academic research experience has given me a rigorous foundation in model development, technical communication, and self-directed work—skills that align with the engineering discipline and collaborative culture this founding team values. As an AI Researcher at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I conducted applied research on StyleGAN and Stable Diffusion, leveraging CUDA, PyTorch, and LoRA on Pace University's HPC cluster for model training and fine-tuning. I was responsible for managing the full model development lifecycle—from data preparation and training runs to inference optimization using vLLM and deployment via Hugging Face—ensuring both performance and secure model serving with testable code. Beyond building the systems myself, I led workshops on GPU programming with CUDA and Mojo, and on building AI Agents with LangChain and LangGraph, for an audience of 50+ students. Designing and delivering those sessions required me to break down complex technical concepts clearly and accessibly—directly mirroring the code review and technical collaboration responsibilities central to this role. This experience has shaped me into an engineer who builds with rigor, thinks through edge cases, and communicates with clarity.

I have always been passionate about accessible, patient-centered care and addressing both medical and social determinants of health, and I envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of Essen Health Care's mission to innovate healthcare delivery in underserved communities. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

